{
  "texts": [
    "Machining processes using traditional rigid grinding have been developed into abrasive belt grinding with its advantages including the ability to reach complex workpiece surface geometries (Pandiyan et al., 2020b).",
    "Grinding belts are equipped with polymer wheels for contact control and belt placement tracks that cover complex surface areas.",
    "Due to the dynamic and interrelated operational parameters, the grinding process with abrasive belts is non-linear and non-uniform (Pandiyan & Tjahjowidodo, 2017).",
    "In the context of the grinding process with abrasive belts, non-linearity refers to the fact that the relationship between the input parameters (such as belt speed, pressure, and grit size) and the output parameters (such as surface roughness, material removal rate, and grinding force) is not linear.",
    "This means that a change in one input parameter does not result in a proportional change in the output parameter."
  ]
}